Orchestrates the three top-level scan operations for CTX: `scan_run` (full summarize from scratch), `check_run` (staleness detection only, no model calls), and `update_run` (check-then-regenerate-only-what's-stale). This is the entry point crate callers (CLI) invoke; it wires together `ctx-summarize`'s generic `summarize`/`summarize_leaf`/`summarize_rollup` engine with this crate's `walker`, `hash`, and `readme` modules.

Key non-obvious detail: prompts are always loaded from `prompts_dir` resolved against the process's current working directory via `load_prompts`, never from the scan target `base` — this is deliberate so the target repo doesn't need to carry CTX's own prompt files, but it means tests or callers that `chdir` unexpectedly will load the wrong prompts.

`summarize<F: Fs, A: Agent>(fs, agent, prompts, targets, approve) -> Result<ScanSummary, ScanError>` is the reusable inner step (generic over fake `Fs`/`Agent` for testing): it runs scope check, delegates to `ctx_summarize::runner::run_with_prompts`, then always writes the README, returning `ScanSummary { leaves_written, rollups_written, readme_written }`. `scan_run` wraps this with a real `StdFs`, walks `base`, and additionally persists the hash tree via `hash::store` after summarizing — note hashes are stored only in `scan_run`, not in bare `summarize`.

`regenerate` (private) is the core of `update_run`'s selective-rebuild logic: it processes `stale.changed_files` (re-summarize leaves), then `stale.orphan_leaves` (delete `.ctx` files whose source vanished), then `stale.stale_dirs` (re-summarize rollups) — order matters because rollups must run after their child leaves are current, and `Staleness.stale_dirs` is documented (in `hash.rs`) as already deepest-first. `update_run` short-circuits and returns early without calling `load_prompts`, `regenerate`, `hash::store`, or `write_readme` when `stale.is_fresh()` — a fresh tree makes zero model calls and touches no files, which is the whole point of the check-first design. When not fresh, it persists the new hash tree and rewrites the README even though `regenerate` doesn't do either.

All three public run functions propagate errors as `ScanError` from walk, scope-check (`approve`-gated to prevent oversized/unintended scans), summarization, hash, and README-write failures — none of them panic on expected failure paths.